to get started with the manuel install we will start with installing our language and keyboard
the following command will list all keymaps for english:
ls /usr/share/kbd/keymaps/**/*.map.gz | grep en

once you have found you keymap we will load it with the following:
loadkeys "file name for keymap"

now we will check we are in uefi:
cat /sys/firmware/efi/fw_platform_size

the command should return 32 or 64 if in uefi

next we will verify our connection with the following:
ping -c 5 archlinux.org 

now we will partition our drives:
lsdisk

now all storage devices should be listed find the name of the one you want to install arch into(mine is mmcblk0)
cfdisk /dev/"device name"

now a gui with your device should open, within the gui select where you want arch to install into(free space for dual boot), use arrow keys to navigate, and enter key to click
once you click on where you want your install we will first make a 512M volume for our bootloader(grub) after that make a second one with however much you want arch to use
keep track of the name of both those new volumes, i will refer to the 512M as vol1 and the custom size one as vol2

follow these commands to format our new volumes:

mkfs.fat -F 32 /dev/vol1
mkfs.btrfs /dev/vol2
mount /dev/vol2 /mnt

now we will mount our disk:
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@home
umount /mnt

now we will compress the volumes:
mount -o compress=zstd,subvol=@ /dev/vol2 /mnt
mkdir -p /mnt/home
mount -o compress=zstd,subvol=@home /dev/vol2 /mnt/home

now we will mount our bootloader:
mkdir -p /mnt/efi
mount /dev/vol1 /mnt/efi

now we will install our packages, if you know what you are doing feel free to add or remove them:
this is the format for the command:
pacstrap -K /mnt pack name 1 pack name 2 etc...
and here are the packages to list in the commands format:
amd-ucode - updates for amd cpu 
base - required
base-devel - dev packages
blueman - bluetooth applet
btrfs-progs - file system management needed for btrfs  
cmake - needed to build certain files
discord - names says it all
efibootmgr - required by grub 
flatpak - needed to install packages using flat hub
git - installs git 
gnome-disk-utility
grim - screenshot tool
grub - bootloader
grub-btrfs - adds btrfs support to grub
impression - used to make bootinstallers in linux
inotify-tools - needed for grub btrfs deamon to spot new snapshots
kitty - personal fav terminal
kitty-shell-intergration
kitty-terminfo
linux - required
linux-firmware - required
ly - login manager
nano - needed for config editing
nautilus - file explorer 
neovim - personal fav IDE
networkmanager - easy network management 
obsidian - note taking app
openrgb - for led control
openssh - to utilize ssh 
pipewire - needed For audio
pipewire-alsa - needed for audio framework
pipewire-pulse - needed for audio framework
pipewire-jack - needed for audio framework
prismlauncher - minecraft java launcher
reflector - manage mirrors for pacman
sudo - to run commands as other users
timeshift - a gui to utilize snapshots  
ttf-bigblueterminal-nerd
vlc - media player
waybar - taskbar for hypr
wireplumber - pipewire session manager
wofi - application search for hypr 

if it fails check its all spelt correctly, if it failed for taking too long just run the command again it can take a few attempts on slower connections

now we will get our mount points as they are now:

genfstab -U /mnt >> /mnt/etc/fstab

and check if they are correct and fine:

cat /mnt/etc/fstab

now we will enter our new system:

arch-chroot /mnt

now we will setup our lang and tty keyboard, enter the following command and uncomment which ever one represents you lang:

nvim /etc/locale.gen (for example i'll uncomment en_AU.UTF-8 UTF-8)

locale-gen (will generate our lang)

now we will need to active our new lang with the following commands:

touch /etc/locale.conf

nvim /etc/locale.conf

to use neovim to type press I and type LANG="enter whatever lang you installed, example:en_AU.UTF-8 UTF-8"
now press esc and type :wq to save and exit (remember how to use neovim it will be used a decent amount)

now to activate our keymaps we got before:

nvim /etc/vconsole.conf

add the following: 

KEYMAPS="the file name of the key maps we installed before"

now we will configure our host name:

touch /etc/hostname

nvim /etc/hostname
(add whatever host name you want i'll use Arch)

touch /etc/hosts

nvim /etc/hosts
(make the file match below with your hostname of course)
127.0.0.1 localhost
::1 localhost
127.0.1.1 Arch

now to set our passwords and make our user:

passwd
*enter your password*

(i am using my name as the example)
useradd -mG wheel michael

passwd michael
*enter password*

run the following command and find "Uncomment to let members of group wheel execute any action" and uncomment the line BELOW IT:
EDITOR=nvim visudo

now we will deploy grub with the following:

grub-install --target=x86_64-efi --efi-directory=/efi --bootloader-id=GRUB  

and generate its config with:

grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg

now enable network manager:

systemctl enable NetworkManager

and exit everything and reboot with the following:

exit
umount -R /mnt
reboot

enter the following upon reboot:

timedatectl set-ntp true

now to set up our snap shots enter the following command and replace execStart=... with ExecStart=/usr/bin/grub-btrfsd --syslog --timeshift-auto:

sudo systemctl edit --full grub-btrfsd

and enable it to run on boot:

sudo systemctl enable grub-btrfsd

now for a few extra packages:

sudo pacman -S --needed git base-devel && git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/yay.git && cd yay && makepkg -si

yay -S timeshift-autosnap

now reboot with the following command and you will have a arch install, if you want a gui keep going if not you can stop here:

reboot

use the following command to install amd drivers, if you dont use amd see the driver installs for whichever you use:

sudo pacman -S mesa vulkan-radeon libva-mesa-driver mesa-vdpau

now for a graphial env:

pacman -S --needed hyprland swaylock wofi waybar

yay -S wlogout

sudo pacman -S xorg-xauth

yay -S ly

sudo systemctl enable ly@tty1.service

now do the following if you are using windows dual boot(skip if not)

sudo pacman -S os-prober

sudo nano /etc/default/grub
(uncomment: GRUB_DISABLE_OS_PROBER=false)
to write and exit nano once uncommented use the following
ctrl + o, ctrl + x

sudo grub-mkconfig -o /boot/grub/grub.cfg

(skip to here)
now to install our final packages:

sudo pacman -S network-manager-applet

flatpak remote-add --if-not-exists flathub https://dl.flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo

flatpak install org.vinegarhq.Sober com.bambulab.BambuStudio com.valvesoftware.Steam app.zen_browser.zen

git clone https://github.com/LazyVim/starter ~/.config/nvim

rm -rf ~/.config/nvim/.git

nvim

once everything is installed you can reboot your system one last time
once you have logged in hypr may prompt you close out of the all
press Super + q and type the following: 
nautilus
in the bottom right there should be an arrow click it and show hidden files
go into .config, hypr
right click the hypr conf and open with kitty 
go to the config i have here and copy it
or alternatively delete the auto config and download mine there if you know how to do so

and do one final reboot and you now have arch fully installed(check the hypr config for the keybinds)
